            {
                "s2_paper_id": "e75653b3519a52eef025911022764837dcbd5415",
                "title": "Non\u2010enzymatic glycation reduces glucose transport in the human cartilage endplate independently of matrix porosity or proteoglycan content",
                "year": 2023,
                "venue": "JOR Spine",
                "citation_count": 1,
                "reference_count": 43,
                "abstract": "Intervertebral disc degeneration is associated with low back pain, which is a leading cause of disability. While the precise causes of disc degeneration are unknown, inadequate nutrient and metabolite transport through the cartilage endplate (CEP) may be one important factor. Prior work shows that CEP transport properties depend on the porosity of the CEP matrix, but little is known about the role of CEP characteristics that could influence transport properties independently from porosity. Here, we show that CEP transport properties depend on the extent of non\u2010enzymatic glycation of the CEP matrix.",
